• no coffee conversation tomorrow, but here’s this: three pictures that describe the season well • 1. Looking put together, 2. organized chaos, 3. Despite pre-packing a healthy lunch, running errands and being on time to babysit, taking a fall and ripping my pants in the Parkside parking lot. • the future really freaks me out and I don’t like change either. I mean, who does? All through January, I’ve tried my best to prepare for the next semester of school and what it will mean. And, honestly, it scared me so much to think about that I didn’t want to bring it to the Lord. Instead, I went on trying to control my life and get everything as ready as I could for what was coming. Backpack ready for the first week. Making sure I have the right books. Meal planning. Setting aside outfits for when I’m running late. You get the point. Right when I thought I was on top of my life and feeling proud of myself, I tripped on my own shoe laces. Books flew out of my hands. And suddenly I was sprawled across the cement. What adult does something that dumb?? And suddenly I was laughing hysterically. I laughed all the way to my car. And then when I thought I was done laughing, I remembered that someone had gasped when I fell. SOMEONE SAW ME? And then I laughed so hard I cried, and then suddenly I really started to cry. Life is so much out of my control, and that’s okay. The next season is just one more thing I have to trust God with, like I’ve trusted Him before. And He won’t let me down. It doesn’t take away all the fear, of course. Falling scared me, and the result hurt, at least for a little bit. But I picked up my books, laughed at myself, and went on with my life. That’s what I have to learn to do when I am not perfect. Which, unfortunately, is most of the time. God’s got me through the unknowns and the failures and the scary things and the future. He’s got you too. That’s all. Have a great weekend 💛 •

• no coffee conversation today • as I’m getting ready for spring break to be over (😭), I’m reflecting on the last few months. They were full of learning new recipes, staying up late with homework, road trips, days with Aiden, crafts and books, youth group, and a couple parties with friends. It’s a season of learning to do things that I’m not good at, being more adventurous, and learning to manage my time and life a *little* better. It’s a season of hearing God’s voice through the day in new ways and stopping to breathe and be thankful for small moments. It’s a season of learning more about God, recognizing what He’s calling me to, and—of course—lots of editing. It’s been wonderful and exhausting… and even through the hard moments, I’m loving it. •

• Mr. and Mrs. Goodwill coming 2024… can’t come soon enough 🥰 I’m still obsessed with these photos… @rebekahlalgeephotos you are the best! Thank you for these 😍 • There’s so much I could say about Aiden. If you know him, you know he works so hard and serves faithfully without complaint, and he hates attention. He’s the rare kind of person who quietly holds everyone around him together. He serves in “boring” but important ways that may go unnoticed by most. Nothing about him is arrogant or flashy. He thinks of everyone before himself. He is no stranger to pain, but he bears it silently and with thanks. He refuses to yell or raise his voice in anger. He is the humblest, wisest, and most patient man I know. And he is quite hilarious when he’s comfortable. For better or worse, he remembers more of what I say than I do. He’s consistently surprising me with how thoughtful he is. I have never been as happy, safe, or at peace as when I’m with him. 

Really, though, I haven’t even gotten to the best part. He is a godly man. That is an enormous understatement. He is disciplined and passionate about God, the church, and the Bible. I have yet to find a question about the Bible that he can’t answer. He consistently challenges, encourages, and prays for me. He puts into practice everything he learns, and his life is a beautiful example of lordship and obedience. There’s no one I trust more to lead me. He makes it easy to follow. 

We have a long road ahead paved with school, work, service, and big decisions, but none of it makes me afraid or anxious. Don’t get me wrong… it’ll be a hard couple years. But I’m really excited and grateful to go through it with my best friend. ❤️ •
